---------------------------------------------------------------  Market action since Sydney’s end of day:  EQUITIES
New York: U.S. stocks climbed, sending the Standard & Poor’s 500
Index to the highest level since May, after American service
industries expanded more than forecast and speculation grew that
the Federal Reserve will join Japan’s efforts to stoke economic
growth.
*JPMorgan Chase & Co. said they will likely beat third-quarter
profit estimates.
*The S&P 500 rallied 2.2 percent to 1,162.33 at 3:18 p.m. in
New York, its biggest gain since Sept. 1.
*The Dow advanced 206.01 points, or 1.9 percent, to 10,957.28.  London: European stocks rose, snapping six days of losses, as
Moody’s Investor Service said it’s impressed with Greece’s
efforts to reform its finances and U.S. service industries
expanded more than forecast.
*The Stoxx Europe 600 Index surged 1.3 percent to 261.18 at
the 4:30 p.m. close in London, the biggest gain in more than a
month.
*National benchmark indexes rose in all of the 18 western
European markets today except for Iceland. Germany’s DAX gained  Tokyo: Japanese stocks climbed, reversing losses after the Bank
of Japan said it will cut its benchmark interest rate and
increase purchases of bonds to combat deflation and stimulate
the economy. The yen weakened.
*The Nikkei 225 Stock Average rose 1.5 percent to 9,518.76
at the 3 p.m. close in Tokyo.
*The broader Topix index climbed 1.2 percent to 832.64.  Sydney/Wellington: Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index fell 0.4
percent to 4,606.90 at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading in
Sydney. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index declined 0.3 percent to
3,218.32 at the 5 p.m. close in Wellington.  FOREIGN EXCHANGE  New York: The dollar dropped to the lowest level since January
against a basket of currencies including the euro and yen on
speculation the Federal Reserve will debase the currency by
increasing purchases of government debt.
*The Dollar Index, which IntercontinentalExchange Inc. uses
to track the greenback against the currencies of six major U.S.
trading partners, dropped 0.9 percent to 77.74 at 2:43 p.m. in
New York.
*The dollar depreciated 1.1 percent to $1.3837 per euro after
touching $1.3851, the weakest level since Feb. 4.
*The yen gained 0.2 percent to 83.22 per dollar. It touched
82.96, the strongest level since Sept. 15, when Japan
acknowledged intervening.  TREASURIES  New York: Treasury 10-year note yields traded near a five-week
low after a report showing service companies in the U.S.
expanded faster than forecast failed to deter speculation the
Federal Reserve will increase asset purchases.
*The yield on the benchmark 10-year note fell 1 basis point,
or 0.01 percentage point, to 2.47 percent at 2:15 p.m. in New
York. It touched 2.43 percent, the lowest level since Aug. 25.
*The 30-year bond yield rose 2 basis points to 3.72 percent
after earlier touching 3.76 percent.  COMMODITIES  GOLD  New York: Gold futures jumped to a record $1,342.60 an ounce as
the dollar sagged, boosting demand for precious metals as
alternative assets. Silver advanced to a 30-year high.
*Gold futures for December delivery rose $23.50, or 1.8
percent, to settle at $1,340.30 at 1:41 p.m. on the Comex in New
York. It was the biggest gain for a most-active contract since
Sept. 14.  METALS  New York: Copper rose to the highest price in 26 months as the
dollar dropped, boosting demand for commodities as alternative
assets. Tin climbed to a record.
*Copper futures for December delivery rose 6.25 cents, or
1.7 percent, to close at $3.7265 a pound at 1:32 p.m. on the
Comex in New York. Earlier, the metal reached $3.745, the
highest price for a most-active contract since July 30, 2008.
*On the LME, copper for delivery in three months rose $112, or
1.4 percent, to $8,176 a metric ton ($3.71 a pound).  OIL  New York: Crude oil surged to the highest level in five months
on speculation that central banks will keep stoking economic
growth as the Bank of Japan  pledged asset purchases and the
dollar fell against the euro.
*Crude oil for November delivery rose $1.36, or 1.7 percent,
to $82.83 a barrel at the 2:30 p.m. close of floor trading on
the New York Mercantile Exchange.
*The contract reached $82.99 he highest level since May 4.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*Australia’s Performance of Construction Index, 9.30 a.m. in
Sydney
*Reserve Bank of Australia’s head of financial stability Luci
Ellis speaks at 9:40 a.m. Sydney time.
*ANZ Bank Chief Executive Officer Michael Smith speaks at
Australian Institute of Company Directors lunch, 1 pm in Sydney  STOCKS TO WATCH: Stocks that may see unusual gains or
losses following news after the close yesterday:
*Rio Tinto Group said it hasn’t made any final decision on its
proposed iron-ore joint venture in Western Australia with BHP
Billiton Ltd.
